{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211057/1958020701/0027.xml":{"full_text":"High-Priced Drug Makers Shudder\nAs FTC Readies Antitrust Action\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nA secret report due to be released soon by the Federal Trade\nCommission is sending drug executives to their tranquillizer bottles. The study, prepared by\nthe Commission's Bureau of Economics, is currently being combed by FTC lawyers for pos\nsible antitrust action against the makers of high priced wonder drugs.\nThe report is expected to appear in early February after nearly seven years of on-again\noff-again preparation. In December it moved from the Bureau of Economics for processing\nby the FTC's Bureau of\ntion and its Litigation Division. In\ndustry sources have interpreted this\nas meaning that while the report it\nself may make \"tame\" reading, com\nmission lawyers will use evidence\ngained during its preparation as the\nbasis of suits against major drug\nmanufacturers.\nAmong the things which have\naroused the curiosity of the commis\nsion are the long-term stability of\ncertain antibiotics prices despite fluc\ntuation in production demand the\nother factors. Other areas of concern\nare mark-ups and patent practices.\nThe report has been a matter of\ncontroversy within the FTC almost\nfrom its inception. It was first dis\ncussed as early as 1951. In July\n1953, the commission passed a reso\nlution authorizing the investigation.\nIt has been repeatedly prodded by\nCongress, which has taken pains to\nprovide funds for the study. However,\nas late as July, 1955, Stephen Spin\ngarn, a former member of the com\nmission, charged that little or nothing\nhad been done to advance the probe.\nCHANGE OF ATTITUDE\nHe also told a House subcommittee\ninvestigating the FTC that the Eisen\nhower-appointed chairman of the\nagency, Edward F. Howry, wanted to\navoid a general review of the patent\nsituation in the drug industry. Many\nexperts believe that patent practices\nlie at the heart of high drug prices.\nHowry has since resigned and been\nreplaced by Chairman John W.\nGwynne.\nGwynne has slowly proceeded to\ninfuse better morale and a more ag\ngressive attitude into the agency. In\nthe meantime, however, the drug work\nresided in the hands of the Bureau\nof Economics under Dr. Simon Whit\nney, a conservative economist, who\nhas remained unenthused about the\ndrug study, according to informed\nobservers.\nThe commission's 1957 report states\nthat antibiotics study was the \"major\nwork\" of the Division of Economic\nEvidence and Reports in Whitney's\nbureau. It complains that very little\neconomic literature exists about the\nrelatively new industry producing\nthe so-called wonder drugs.\nA release date in early summer had\nbeen indicated. However, in a turn\nabout, the commission pushed the date\nforward to Labor Day and issued a\nnew questionnaire to the industry.\nDELAYS DOG REPORT\nSince then delays have continued\nto dog the report. Conflict is believed\nto have developed between Whitney\nand Harry Babcock, director of the\nBureau of Investigation, who report\nedly favors a crackdown on the drug\nmakers.\nLast December the new version pre\npared by Whitney's subordinates was\npassed on to Babcock's unit and to\nthe Litigation Division and the Gen\neral Counsel's office. This is normal\nprocedure preliminary to release. But\nit gives these \"police\" units of the\nagency a chance to delete material\nthe presence of which might prejudice\nfuture legal action against the in\ndustry involved.\nAs a result, the industry has a bad\ncase of jitters. Typical of its state is\nthe comment of a leading trade paper:\n\"No matter how tame, publication of\nFTC's antibiotics report probably will\nfocus public and congressional atten\ntion on the 'high cost of medicine'\ncontroversy\nThe high cost of medicine is of leg\nitimate concern in a nation where\nmedical care costs for worker fami\nlies has zoomed 38 per cent since\n1947-49. According to the Depart\nment of Labor, medical costs have\nrisen more than any other major item\nin the cost of living.\nANTIBIOTIC COSTS\nPart of this cost goes for the 1,\n200,000 prescriptions that are filled\nby druggists across the nation every\nday. The drug industry sells approxi\nmately $2.8 billion worth of medicines\na year, and collects a before-tax prof\nit of about half a billion.\nInvestiga-*-\u2014\nOf these totals, antibiotics are be\nlieved to account for 25 per cent of\nall prescriptions and some 40 per cent\nof the dollar value of drug sales.\nMold-grown medicines first developed\nfor commercial use in 1943, antibiot\nics now are used to fight everything\nfrom pneumonia to gonorrhea. Their\nmulti-syllabic names haij\u00df become\nhousehold words. But everyone, from\nmembers of Congress to just plain,\nJoe Doakes, has at one time or an\nother complained about their terrific\nprices, ranging as high as 80 cents\nto $1 per capsule.\nCritics of the industry find it in\ntriguing that penicillin prices have\ndropped sharply from their original\nhigh levels, while antibiotics devel\noped subsequently have remained\nhigh priced. They note that penicillin\nis not protected by patent, but that\nthe new wonder drug formulas are\nfiercely hoarded by their manufac\nturers. Court records are full of com\nplicated cases in which giant drug\nfirms fight it out over antibiotic\npatents.\nAs a result, many believe that the\nindustry has used illegal or un-ethical\nmeans to maintain its price levels via\nprice fixing or patent arrangements.\nThe industry's stock reply to the\naccusation that it overcharges is that\nit must spend $75 million to $100\nmillion for research and development.\nIt is more reticent, however, about the\nFrench Luring U.S. Oil Giants\nTo Sahara Desert-With a Catch\nWill big American oil companies\n\u2014and perhaps U. S. soldiers\u2014\"find\nthemselves in the midst of an increas\ningly bloody conflict\" in the Sahara\ndesert? That question is raised by an\narticle in THE REPORTER maga\nzine and a news report in the NEW\nYORK TIMES. The story they tell\nboils down to this:\nFor a long time, France has been\nfighting a costly war to hold down\nrebellious Arabs in Algeria, fighting\nfor independence. Many French are\ngrowing tired of the enormous ex\npense of this war. So the French\ngovernment sought, and found, a\nway to make the rewards of the\nfighting seem worthwhile.\nThe rewards are in oil, which has\nbeen discovered in huge quantities\nin the Sahara, part of Algeria. This\nweek, according to the TIMES, the\nfirst oil flowed through the first\npipeline. The latter is a small and\n\"temporary\" one and won't deliver\nenough oil to make it an \"economic\"\nsuccess. But it means a lot \"psycho\nlogically\" to the French government,\nboth the TIMES and the REPORTER\nmagazine say. They explain it this\nway;\nFrance now has to buy its oil from\nthe 'International Cartel\" companies,\nat high cost which is a heavy burden\non the French economy, Sahara oil\nwould free France from most of that\nburden. But, to be sure of getting the\noil, France will have to continue its\nexpensive war igainst the rebellious\nArabs\u2014unless the latter can be con\nvinced their cause is hopeless.\nFor that purpose, the French gov\nernment has been offering Sahara\ndeals to foreign oil companies, par\nticularly the giant American concerns\nwhich are members of the Interna\ntional Cartel, Many companies are\nshowing interest in these deals, says\nREPORTER magazine, and it pictures\nthe result as follows;\n\"Since nearly all the U. S. ventures\nwill have French participation, it\nwill make them direct partners. Many\nFrench officials and businessmen con\nnected with Sahara affairs privately\nthink that such a partnership'would\ncommit the U. S. oil companies fully\non the side of France in Algeria, since\nit would give them a direct stake in I\n$300 million it spends to ballyhoo its\nproducts among doctors.\n'ETHICAL DRUGS'\nUnlike proprietary drugs which\nmay be sold without prescription, the\nso-called \"ethical drugs\" require a\ndoctor's order before they may be\nsold. As a consequence, the drug\nmakers bombard the nation's 225,000\ndoctors with fancy promotional liter\nature. Unlike other advertising, this\nmaterial is exempt from FTC regula\ntion, The FTC watches other adver\ntising material to stop deceptive prac\ntices.\nIn addition, the drug makers em\nploy an estimated 20,000 salesmen\u2014\nalmost one for every 10 doctors\u2014to\npush their brands. They also shower\nsamples and other gifts on doctors,\nand medical personnel.\nIt is the consumer who pays for all\nof this.\nDrug prices are also under scrutiny\nby the Department of Justice. Under\nurging by a House subcommittee that\ninvestigated the prices drug makers\ncharged Uncle Sam for vaccines, the\nJustice Department has a grand jury\nprobe under way in Trenton, N. J.,\nto study the identical bids put for\nward to the government by manufac\nturers of Salk polio vaccine. Simul\ntaneously, the department is prose\ncuting the Parke-Davis Co. for al\nlegedly trying to restrict its channels\nof distribution in violation of the anti\ntrust laws.\u2014LABOR'S DAILY.\nthe maintenance of French authority\nover the area.\n\"These circles,\" the REPORTER\ncontinues, \"hope that this treatment\nwould have an effect on the U. S.\nState Department's approach to the\nAlgerian question, similar to that\nwhich American oil operations in the\nMiddle East have on U. S. policy\nthere.\nThe TIMES adds that \"the French\nattach considerable importance to the\nreported willingness of Standard Oil\nof New Jersey to invest huge sums on\na 50-50 basis with French oil compa\nnies,\" because such reports help to\nconvince the Algerian Arabs that the\nU. S. government is not on their side\nin their war for independence.\nLABOR.\n9f\nGOP Hunts Nicer\nWord For Recession\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014 (NFU)\u2014\nJust as a rose by any other name is\nstill a rose, so a recession is still a\nrecession no matter what it's called.\nNevertheless the optimistic word\nsmiths around Washington these days\nkeep trying to avoid that horrid word\n\"recession\". They talk about a \"roll\ning readjustment\" or a \"modest de\ncline\" or a \"cyclinal adjustment\".\nIn a rosy New Years Day message\nto the American people, Secretary of\nCommerce Sinclair Weeks talked of a\n\"mild dip\" which he said would turn\ninto a \"climb\" before the year was\nout.\n_ _\nFrom where I sit.' he said \"the\ntwelve-month outlook is far better\nthan nail-biting pessimists think\nSecretary Weeks must not have\nbeen sitting in front of the business\nnewspapers when he said that. Their\nheadlines were telling of auto fac\ntory layoffs, a slow-down in machine\nt\u00ae? 1 orders, cancellations of tanker\nships and so on all adding up to a\npossible unemployment total of 5,\n900,000 men -by February.\nMen in general judge more from\nappearances than from reality. All\nmen have eyes, but few have the gift\nof penetration.\u2014MACHIAVELLI.\nA Montanan's\nWASHINGTON NOTEBOOK\nBy BRITT ENGLUND, Sec'y. of Cong. Lee Metcalf\nAs this is written, Congressman\nAnderson's bill to authorize settle\nment with the Crow Indians for right\nof-way for Yellowtail Dam had just\ncleared the last hurdle on its way\nto the floor of the House. The House\nmay have taken action by the time\nthis is in print.\nChairman Engle of the House In\nterior Committee and Congressman\nMetcalf, a member of that commit\ntee, made the pitch for Yellowtail be\nfore the House Rules Committee. The\nRules Committee is the legislative\ntraffic cop, deciding whether, and\nunder what conditions, a bill will be\ntaken up on the floor.\nAfter the hearing, the committee\nwaved the bill through.\nThe Senate has passed a Murray\nMansfield bill to pay the Crows $5\nmillion, an amount previously vetoed\nby President Eisenhower at the urg\ning of then-Congressman Fjare. Con\ngressman Anderson's House bill was\namended in committee to $2% mil\nlion. Ten Republican members of the\nHouse Interior Committee have indi\ncated they will move on the floor\nto chop the figure to $1% million,\nthe figure first approved by the\nHouse in 1956.\nOriginally the Crows put a $50\nmillion price tag on the 5,700 acres\nneeded for the dam and reservoir.\nThe Interior Department offered\n$1% million. A negotiated price of\n$5 million was agreed on by every\nbody but President Eisenhower and\nCongrssman Fjare.\nCHARITY BEGINS AT HOME\nResource development, like charity,\nbegins at home\u2014or ought to, accord\ning to Congressman Metcalf.\nHe said so last week during a for\neign policy discussion in the House.\nMetcalf laid it out for his colleagues\nthis way:\n1. Under President Eisenhower's\nbudget for the year beginning July 1\nthere would be no new starts on flood\ncontrol or reclamation projects in\nthis country.\n2. Yet, the same budget provides\nU. S. aid for building multipurpose\ndams abroad.\nMetcalf quoted from a House com\nmittee report that some of the proj\nects being built abroad are unfeasible.\nWe are building more multipur\npose dams abroad than we are build\ning in our own country,\" Metcalf\nsaid. \"It becomes very difficult for\nme to go along with the present pro\ngram of no new starts in reclamation\nand no new starts in the development\nof multipurpose dams, and then to\nfind that some of this economic aid\na\nabroad is being given for projects that\nare fiscally unfeasible and which\ncould not be authorized by a legisla\ntive committee of this Congress.\nAt about the same time, Senator\nMurray was speaking on a related\nsubject on the floor of the Senate.\nHis point; Administrative agencies\ndon't always give congressional com\nmittees the whole story on pending\nnatural resource development pro\nposals.\n\nMaterial comes to the committees,\nSenator Murray said, but the agen\ncies are \"selective\" in their presenta\ntion. Frequently the committees have\nto ask for such important informa\ntion as cost allocation, period for\nrepayment of the power investment\nand the formula for determining the\ninterest rate.\nThis results in\n'unnecessary de\nlays\" in consideration of the legisla\ntion, Senator Murray said.\nFollowing his speech, the Senate\npassed his resolution recommending\nthat the Administration get all the\nnecessary background information on\nproposed multipurpose projects to the\ncommittees at one time.\nWOOL\nThe Senate Agriculture Committee\nhas sche dul4d hearings February 6\nand 7 on bill among them those by\nMontanans in Congress, to extend\nfor four years the provisions of the\nNati onal Wool Act.\nThe Act is an ap pii cat ion of the\n\u00ab\u00dfrannan plan\" production payment\nprincip]e to wool. When he was Sec\nretary D f Agriclture Charles Bran\nnan wou id have used it widely instead\nQ f j us f. f or one commodity.\nUnder the Act, wool sells for what\never it will bring in the market,\nDomestic producers receive direct\npayments for the difference between\nthe average market price for the sea\nson and a pre-determined support\nlevel, which' may run more than 100\nper cent of parity. The high support\nlevel is to encourage production of\nwool. Domestic production would be\nexpanded to 300 million pounds a\nyear, an amount essential for na\ntional security. Last year's domestic\nproduction was about 240 million\npounds. Money for the incentive pay\nment comes from the tariff on im\nported wool.\nREPORT TO MONTANA\nAnother congressional report by\nthe Montana delegation is on its way\nhome. Senators Murray and Mans\nfield, Congressmen Metcalf and An\nderson met in the radio-TV studio\nin the Capitol one morning last week\nto make the \"simulcast\"\u2014a 15-min\nute program simultaneously filmed\nfor television and taped for broad\ncast.\nAs with previous early-session pro\ngrams, this round-table discussion\ncovers legislation and appropriations\nof importance to Montanans. The pro\nwas sent to radio and TV\nstation in the State.\nBPR MOVE\nMontanans in Congress have been\nable to delay\u2014at least temporarily\u2014\nthe proposal to move the Bureau of\nPublic Roads regional office from\nMissoula to Helena and Vancouver,\nWash.\nSecretary of Commerce Weeks went\nalong with a delegation request and\nlate last week held up the final de\ncision on the move until congressional\nand administration leaders have a\nchance to go over new evidence being\nsubmitted by the Missoula Chamber\nof Commerce.\nAbout a year ago, misinformation\nwas circulated in the Treasure State\nabout the committee assignments of\nMontanans in Congress.\nThe Republican state chairman is\nsued an \"expression of regret\" that\nCongressman Metcalf \"failed to get\nreappointed\" to the House Interior\nand Insular Affairs Committee, which\nhas jurisdiction over the natural re\nsources so important to Montana.\nMain thing wrong with the statement\nwas that it wasn't true. Metcalf con\ntinued to serve on the committee\u2014\nstill does.\nTo head off a possible repetition,\nhere are leadership and committee\nassignments of the Montana delega\ntion in this Congress.\nSenator Murray: Chairman of the\nSenate Interior and Insular Affairs\nCommittee and of its Minerals, Ma\nterials and Fuels subcommittee;\nsenior majority member of the Labor\nand Public Welfare Committee and\nchairman of its Education subcom\nmittee.\nSenator Mansfield: Member of the\nForeign Relations and Rules Commit\ntee; majority whip, the No. 2 man\nin the Democratic leadership of the\nSenate.\nBoth senators are on the nine-man\nMajority Policy Committee\u2014Montana\nbeing the only state ever to have had\nboth its senators on this policy group.\nCongressman Metcalf: Member of\nInterior and Insular Affairs Com\nmittee, four of its subcommittees\u2014\nIrrigation and Reclamation, Mines\nand Mining, Public Lands, and Indian\nAffairs\u2014and of its special Coal Re\nsearch subcommittee; member of the\nEducation and Labor Committee and\nof its General Education subcommit\ntee.\nCongressman Anderson; Member of\nthe Banking and Currency Commit\ntee, which has jurisdiction over home\nloans, small business, farm credit and\nmonetary policy. Before\nlands on Anderson for not having\nsubcommittee assignments\u2014this\nmittee has no subcommittees.\nWhile putting this piece together,\nwe were reminded that Montana has\nhad a seat on the House Interior,\nor predecessor, Committee for\nthan 20 years. The day that Congress\nman James O'Connor died in 1945,\nCongressman Mansfield resigned from\nthe House Foreign Affairs Commit\ntee and asked assignment to O'Con\nnor's Reclamation, Indian Affairs and\nPublic Lands Committees so Montana\nwould not lose her representation\nthere.\nMansfield held the fort on these\ncommittees until Cong. D'Ewart\nported for duty later that year. Then\nMike went back to Foreign Affairs,\nhaving sacrificed his seniority in Mon\ntana's interest.\nsomeone\ncom\nmore\nre","height":"20451","width":"14028"}}
